edu.harvard.data.schema.identity

Class IdentitySchema

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.harvard.data.schema.identity.IdentitySchema

  • public class IdentitySchema
extends Object
    The Identity Schema defines the set of user identifiers in a data set. It is generally specified through a JSON object with the following structure: 
     
 { "table_name" : {
     "identifying_column_name" : ["IdentityType"],
     "multiplexed_column_name" : ["IdentityType1", "IdentityType2"],
     },
 { "table_name2" : {
     "identifying_column_name" : ["IdentityType"],
     "confidential_column_name" : ["Other"]
     }
 }
    For example, the Canvas Data identity specification contains the following table declaration: 
     
 "pseudonym_dim": {
   "user_id": ["CanvasDataID"],
   "canvas_id": ["CanvasID"],
   "sis_user_id": ["HUID", "XID"],
   "unique_name": ["Other"]
   "id": ["Other"],
 },
    In this table (pseudonym_dim), we see examples of several different identifying columns. The user_id column contains the IdentifierType.CanvasDataID for this individual (this is the main identifier for the Canvas Data set). The table also has second identifier of type IdentifierType.CanvasID which, although it is not the main identifer in the data set is still a unique identifier for this individual. In this case, the Canvas ID can be used to look up an individual's account on the Canvas platform.

    The field sis_user_id contains a key into an external Student Information System, which was fed into Canvas from an on-campus source. In Harvard's case, this column could contain either an official Harvard ID (an IdentifierType.HUID), or a secondary IdentifierType.XID, typically given to guests or other associated individuals. Since two identifier types are multiplexed into a single column, we can rely on the regular expressions specified by IdentifierType.getPattern() to determine which is which.

    Finally, the unique_name and id columns contain information which is confidential but does not contribute to the referential integrity of the data set (for example, the unique_name column contains a user's e-mail address in Harvard's instance of the Canvas Data set). In this case we specify the fields as IdentifierType.Other to indicate that they should be scrubbed by the identity phase of the data pipeline, but that they should not be replaced by anything.

    The resulting schema produced by this transformer for the pseudonym_dim table is almost identical to the input schema, but has the following differences:

    • The five fields user_id, canvas_id, sis_user_id, unique_name and id have been removed.
    • Three new fields, each typed as String have been added: user_id_research_uuid, canvas_id_research_uuid and sis_user_id_research_uuid.

    We add a research UUID for each field even though, in this case, they all hold the same value. In some cases the research UUID values will differ between fields. For example, the Canvas Data table submission_dim has this identifier specification: 

     
 "submission_dim": {
   "user_id": ["CanvasDataID"],
   "grader_id": ["CanvasDataID"]
 },
    In this case, there are CanvasDataID values for two unique individuals; the student who submitted an assignment, and the individual who graded that assignment. When we have multiple instances of the data set's main identifier in a single table, we need to retain the identities of both individuals, and so here we would see different values for user_id_research_uuid and grader_id_research_uuid.

      • get

        public Map<String,List<IdentifierType>> get(String tableName)
        Get the identifier types for a single table as defined by this schema.
        Parameters:
        tableName - the name of the table for which to find identifiers.
        Returns:
        a Map from identifier column name to a List of IdentifierType values. The identifiers are returned as a List because multiple identifiers may be multiplexed into a single column in a data set.

      • read

        public static IdentitySchema read(String jsonResource)
                           throws IOException
        Parse a JSON document to extract an IdentitySchema. The JSON document is specified as a Java classpath resource name, and must be formatted as described in this class description.
        Parameters:
        jsonResource - the name of a resource containing a well-formed JSON document describing an identity schema. The resource must be accessible to the class loader that loaded this class.
        Returns:
        an IdentitySchema containing the data defined in the JSON resource.
        Throws:
        IOException - if and error occurs when reading or parsing the JSON resource.
